When Shakespeare was penning his plays, I believe standardized spelling 
was a concept that did not exist.  That did not stop publishers from 
publishing books.  I understand times have changed since 1600.  
Nevertheless, the fact that publishers &quot;want&quot; a standardized spelling 
has more to do with tradition than necessity I expect.  In the last four 
centuries, the idea that there is a &quot;standard spelling&quot; is now firmly 
entrenched, and we have seen the problems that has caused in English.  
Once a spelling is &quot;fixed,&quot; no one has the authority to change it in the 
future.  We need to throw out the concept of one correct spelling.  
Otherwise, I cannot see how we are to continue to modernize our spelling 
to keep pace with the changes in pronunciation.

What if publishers edited their authors but did not feel compelled to 
modify their spelling and accepted that there can be variations from one 
country to the next or from one major accent  to another major accent?  
Obviously, most authors are sending their publishers digital versions of 
their works these days, rather than typed or penned manuscripts.

Another issue is involves the changes the publishing industry will 
undergo in the future.  Before long, it may be that books will be 
printed as the demand calls for them, and the concept of a first 
printing of a certain number of copies may disappear from the industry 
altogether.  The next step is already appearing.  My wife recently 
bought me a Kindle from Amazon.  It downloads books off the web directly 
into its memory.  There is no printed form per se.  That being the case, 
when QS is adopted, it would be child&#39;s play to print a version in RP or 
General American or General Indian English and let the software handle 
the spelling conversions from one accent to another.  An e-book user may 
be given the choice to pick the accent to have he book delivered in with 
no more concern wasted on spelling than I waste worrying whether I will 
be able to understand an Englishman speaking RP.  In other words -- none.

Paige

